          "infinitive": {
            "reveal": "ringraziare - to thank",
            "bucket": "vocabulary.it.ringraziare.translation"
          }
        }
      }
    ],
    "explanation": "'Gentile dottoressa, La ringrazio per il Suo tempo' means 'Dear Doctor, thank you for your time'. Ringraziare takes a direct object → formal DOP La. The form is tied to formal address (Lei), not to biological gender: La would also be correct for a male addressee. Common miss: Le (the IOP).",
    "examiner_note": "Common miss: 'Le' (using the IOP, which would be 'to you'). Diagnostic: ringraziare is transitive.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_dop_elide_01",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "direct_object.elision_before_vowel",
    "difficulty": 2,
    "cefr_level_target": "B1",
    "prompt": "Write the standard elided form: 'la + ho visto' (referring to her) → '____ ho visto.' (use the contracted form)",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.direct_object.elision_before_vowel",
        "label": "lo/la → l' before a vowel",
        "any_phrases": [
          "l'"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "la ho",
          "lo ho",
          "l ho"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [
      {
        "lemma": "visto",
        "language": "it",
        "aspects": {
          "infinitive": {
            "reveal": "vedere - to see",
            "bucket": "vocabulary.it.vedere.translation"
          }
        }
      }
    ],
    "explanation": "'L'ho visto' (referring to her) means 'I saw her'. When a vowel meets a vowel, Italian drops the first one. Singular DOPs lo/la undergo elision to l' before a vowel-initial verb. The participle still agrees with the underlying gender, even though the clitic looks identical for masc and fem.",
    "examiner_note": "Common miss: 'la ho' (failure to elide). Strict elision is the standard register; spoken Italian almost always elides too.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_dop_elide_02",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "direct_object.elision_before_vowel",
    "difficulty": 2,
    "cefr_level_target": "B1",
    "prompt": "Choose the standard form. 'Have you seen Marco?' 'Yes, ____ ho visto.'",
    "type": "mcq",
    "marks": 1,
    "choices": [
      "l'",
      "lo",
      "gli",
      "li'"
    ],
    "answer_index": 0,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.direct_object.elision_before_vowel",
        "label": "elision lo → l' before ho",
        "any_phrases": [
          "l'"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "lo",
          "gli"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'Hai visto Marco? Sì, l'ho visto' means 'Have you seen Marco? Yes, I've seen him'. Singular lo/la undergo elision to l' before a vowel-initial verb. The apostrophe is obligatory in standard written register.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_dop_elide_03",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "direct_object.elision_before_vowel",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Choose the right form. 'Have you seen them (the children)?' 'Yes, ____ ho visti.' (i bambini)",
    "type": "mcq",
    "marks": 1,
    "choices": [
      "li",
      "l'",
      "lo",
      "gli"
    ],
    "answer_index": 0,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.direct_object.elision_before_vowel",
        "label": "li/le do NOT elide",
        "any_phrases": [
          "li"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "l'",
          "lo"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [
      {
        "lemma": "bambini",
        "language": "it",
        "aspects": {
          "translation": {
            "reveal": "bambino - child",
            "bucket": "vocabulary.it.bambino.translation"
          }
        }
      }
    ],
    "explanation": "'Hai visto i bambini? Sì, li ho visti' means 'Have you seen the children? Yes, I've seen them'. Italian elision is selective: it applies to singular lo/la, but the plural DOPs li and le do NOT elide. The 'l'ho visti' form would be ambiguous with the singular, and it's not used.",
    "examiner_note": "Diagnostic: avoids over-extending the elision rule from singular to plural.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
