          }
        }
      }
    ],
    "explanation": "'Hai delle penne? Me ne dai una?' means 'Have you got any pens? Will you give me one?'. Partitive ne combines with an IOP, with the vowel change applying to the IOP. Stack: mi → me, then me + ne, giving 'me ne dai una' = 'you give me one of them'.",
    "examiner_note": "Tests the me-ne family, a hot-spot pattern at B1-B2.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_comb_glielo_01",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "combined.glielo_family",
    "difficulty": 2,
    "cefr_level_target": "B1",
    "prompt": "Combine 'gli + lo' (to him + it) → ____",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.combined.glielo_family",
        "label": "gli + lo → glielo (one word)",
        "any_phrases": [
          "glielo"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "gli lo",
          "glie lo",
          "gli'lo"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'glielo' = 'it to him'. In the glielo family, the 3rd-person IOP (gli or le) combines with a DOP and is written as one word. The IOP shifts to glie-. Stack: gli + lo → glielo.",
    "examiner_note": "Hot spot. Common miss: 'gli lo' (separated, two words). The cluster is always written together.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
