          "A me",
          "a me"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "Mi",
          "Io"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'A me piace il caffè' means 'I like coffee' (with emphasis on 'me'). For emphasis, Italian swaps the clitic for the stressed pronoun, which carries its preposition. 'A me piace' replaces plain 'mi piace' to put the focus on the experiencer.",
    "examiner_note": "The bare 'a me piace' (without the clitic doubled) is the typical emphatic frame. In contrastive contexts ('a me piace, a lui no') the doubling is sometimes added.",
    "version": 1
  },
