        "label": "Stressed lei post-verb for DO contrast",
        "any_phrases": [
          "lei"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "la",
          "le"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'Vedo lui, non lei' means 'I see him, not her'. Stressed pronouns sit post-verb when the role is direct object, used for contrast or emphasis. The clitic la would lose the contrastive force; 'vedo lei' carries it.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_spec_stressed_03",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "special.stressed_forms",
    "difficulty": 2,
    "cefr_level_target": "B1",
    "prompt": "Complete after the preposition: 'Vuoi venire con ____?' (= with me)",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.stressed_forms",
        "label": "Stressed me after preposition",
        "any_phrases": [
          "me"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "mi",
          "io"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'Vuoi venire con me?' means 'Do you want to come with me?'. After any preposition (con, per, di, da, su, etc.), Italian uses the stressed pronoun, not the clitic. 'Con mi' isn't grammatical; the form is 'con me'.",
    "examiner_note": "Foundational rule. Common miss: 'con mi'.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_spec_fcap_01",
