    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "special.formal_lei_capitalisation",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Capitalise the formal pronouns. 'Gentile signora, la ringrazio per la sua gentilezza.' → 'Gentile signora, ____ ringrazio per la ____ gentilezza.'",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 2,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.formal_lei_capitalisation",
        "label": "Capitalise formal La (DOP)",
        "any_phrases": [
          "La"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "la"
        ]
      },
      {
        "order_index": 1,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.formal_lei_capitalisation",
        "label": "Capitalise formal possessive Sua",
        "any_phrases": [
          "Sua"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "sua"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [
      {
        "lemma": "gentilezza",
        "language": "it",
        "aspects": {
          "translation": {
            "reveal": "gentilezza - kindness",
            "bucket": "vocabulary.it.gentilezza.translation"
          }
        }
      }
    ],
    "explanation": "'Gentile signora, La ringrazio per la Sua gentilezza' means 'Dear madam, I thank you for your kindness'. Formal correspondence in Italian uses capitalisation as a mark of respect. The pronouns of formal address (La, Le, Lei, Loro) and their possessives (Suo, Sua, Suoi, Sue) take a capital. Optional in casual writing.",
    "examiner_note": "Two markpoints. Tests the capitalisation convention rather than form choice.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_spec_fcap_02",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "special.formal_lei_capitalisation",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Complete the formal-Lei reflexive on this sign (capital or lowercase both fine): 'Prego, ____ accomodi.'",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.formal_lei_capitalisation",
        "label": "Reflexive si/Si in formal address (both credited)",
        "any_phrases": [
          "Si",
          "si"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "ti",
          "lo"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'Prego, Si accomodi' means 'Please, make yourself comfortable'. Italian's formal-address capitalisation convention covers the formal pronouns (Lei, La, Le) and their possessives. The reflexive si referring to Lei is variable: the prescriptive convention capitalises it (Si), but modern usage commonly leaves it lowercase. Both are credited here.",
    "examiner_note": "Both Si (prescriptive) and si (modern) credit. The pedagogy is recognition of the convention, not enforcement of the capital.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_spec_dislo_01",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "special.pronoun_then_subject_noun",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Complete: 'La pizza, ____ ho mangiata tutta.' (note the participle ending)",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.left_dislocation_with_pp_agreement",
        "label": "Resumptive DOP after fronted topic, with PP agreement",
        "any_phrases": [
          "l'",
          "la"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "lo",
          "le"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [
      {
        "lemma": "pizza",
        "language": "it",
        "aspects": {
          "translation": {
            "reveal": "pizza - pizza",
            "bucket": "vocabulary.it.pizza.translation"
          },
          "gender": {
            "reveal": "feminine (f)",
            "bucket": "vocabulary.it.pizza.gender"
          }
        }
      }
    ],
    "explanation": "'La pizza, l'ho mangiata tutta' means 'The pizza — I ate it all'. Italian often puts the topic at the start; this is left-dislocation. The fronted direct object la pizza has to be resumed by a clitic: here la (f.sg), elided to l' before ho. The participle mangiata agrees with the fronted f.sg DO through the preceding-DOP rule.",
    "examiner_note": "Cross-references the with_avere agreement bucket. Common miss: omitting the resumption ('La pizza, ho mangiato tutta') — ungrammatical in standard Italian.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_spec_dislo_02",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "special.pronoun_then_subject_noun",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Complete: 'A Marco, ____ ho già parlato.'",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.pronoun_then_subject_noun",
        "label": "Resumptive IOP after fronted a-phrase",
        "any_phrases": [
          "gli"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "lo",
          "li",
          "lui"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'A Marco, gli ho già parlato' means 'Marco — I've already spoken to him'. Italian's fronting can put an indirect-object phrase at the start. 'A Marco' is fronted and resumed by the IOP gli. The everyday spoken pattern.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_spec_dislo_03",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "special.pronoun_then_subject_noun",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Complete: 'Quel libro, ____ ha prestato Marco.' (= it was Marco who lent it to me)",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.pronoun_then_subject_noun",
        "label": "Resumptive cluster: IOP + DOP after fronted topic",
        "any_phrases": [
          "me l'",
          "me lo"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "mi lo",
          "lo me",
          "mel'",
          "melo"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [
      {
        "lemma": "prestato",
        "language": "it",
        "aspects": {
          "infinitive": {
            "reveal": "prestare - to lend",
            "bucket": "vocabulary.it.prestare.translation"
          }
        }
      }
    ],
    "explanation": "'Quel libro, me l'ha prestato Marco' means 'That book — Marco lent it to me'. Italian often puts the topic at the start; this is fronting. The fronted direct object then has to be resumed by a DOP: here lo (m.sg, libro), elided to l' before 'ha'. The 'to me' part is the IOP, normally mi but it becomes me when it precedes another clitic. Stack: me + l' giving 'me l'ha prestato Marco'.",
    "examiner_note": "Combines dislocation, combined clitics, vowel change, and elision. A heavy item; the bucket attribution focuses on the dislocation pattern.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_dop_nonelide_01",
