  {
    "external_id": "op_spec_dislo_04",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "special.pronoun_then_subject_noun",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Complete: 'I biglietti, ____ ha dati ieri Paolo.' (= Paolo gave them to me yesterday)",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.left_dislocation_with_pp_agreement",
        "label": "Dislocation + cluster (me li) + PP agreement (m.pl)",
        "any_phrases": [
          "me li",
          "Me li"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "mi li",
          "me l'",
          "lo me",
          "Meli",
          "meli"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'I biglietti, me li ha dati ieri Paolo' means 'The tickets — Paolo gave them to me yesterday'. The fronted topic 'i biglietti' (m.pl) is resumed by a cluster. The IOP mi shifts to me before the DOP li. Participle 'dati' shows the m.pl agreement with the preceding DOP. Stack: me + li + ha + dati.",
    "examiner_note": "Combines dislocation, cluster, vowel change, and PP agreement. Hot pattern in spoken Italian.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_spec_lo_neut_04",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "special.lo_neutral",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Complete: 'Hai detto a Marco che era invitato?' 'Sì, ____ ho detto.'",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.special.lo_neutral",
        "label": "Neuter lo + IOP gli → glielo in cluster",
        "any_phrases": [
          "gliel'",
          "glielo"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "gli lo",
          "lo gli"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'Hai detto a Marco che era invitato? Sì, gliel'ho detto' means 'Did you tell Marco he was invited? Yes, I told him'. The 'it' here is the embedded clause ('that he was invited'), resumed by neuter lo. The IOP gli combines with neuter lo through the glielo-family transform. Elided to gliel' before ho. Stack: gliel' + ho + detto.",
    "examiner_note": "Tests neuter lo in cluster context.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_comb_joined_01",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Choose the standard-register written form. 'Will you give it (the book) to me?'",
    "type": "mcq",
    "marks": 1,
    "choices": [
      "Me lo dai?",
      "Melo dai?",
      "Me-lo dai?",
      "Mel dai?"
    ],
    "answer_index": 0,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
        "label": "Pre-verb cluster stays as two words",
        "any_phrases": [
          "Me lo dai"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "Melo dai",
          "Me-lo dai",
          "Mel dai"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'Me lo dai?' means 'Will you give it to me?'. Italian's separated cluster stays as two written words in pre-verb position: me lo, te la, ce ne. The joined form melo is the joined cluster pattern, which only applies post-verb (dammelo, vedermelo). Over-generalising the joining is a common error.",
    "examiner_note": "Hot diagnostic for the joined-when-separate confusion.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_comb_joined_02",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Two written words or one? Choose the correct standard-register form for each.",
    "type": "mcq",
    "marks": 1,
    "choices": [
      "me lo dai / dammelo (separate pre-verb, joined attached)",
      "melo dai / dammelo",
      "me lo dai / dami lo",
      "melo dai / dami lo"
    ],
    "answer_index": 0,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
        "label": "Diagnostic: separate pre-verb, joined post-verb",
        "any_phrases": [
          "me lo dai / dammelo"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "melo dai",
          "dami lo"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'me lo dai' means 'will you give it to me?' and 'dammelo' means 'give it to me!' — same cluster, different placement rules. Italian splits the convention by position. Pre-verb gives the separated cluster (me lo dai). Attached to an infinitive, gerund, or tu/noi/voi imperative gives the joined cluster (dammelo). Same sounds, different spelling.",
    "examiner_note": "Tests recognition of the contrast directly.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_comb_joined_03",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Complete: 'Quante mele vuoi?' '____ dai tre, per favore.' (= give me three of them)",
    "type": "short",
    "marks": 1,
    "prompt_supplies_base_form": false,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
        "label": "me ne stays as two words pre-verb",
        "any_phrases": [
          "Me ne"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "Mene",
          "mene",
          "Me-ne"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "'Quante mele vuoi? Me ne dai tre, per favore' means 'How many apples do you want? Give me three of them, please'. Pre-verb the cluster is separated: me ne stays as two words. The joined form mene only applies post-verb (parlamene, dammene). Over-generalising the joining gives the error.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_comb_joined_04",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
    "prompt": "Spot the error. Which sentence is written incorrectly?",
    "type": "mcq",
    "marks": 1,
    "choices": [
      "Cela voglio dare. (= I want to give it to her)",
      "Vogliamo darcelo subito.",
      "Glielo abbiamo già detto.",
      "Te ne porto due."
    ],
    "answer_index": 0,
    "markpoints": [
      {
        "order_index": 0,
        "credit": 1.0,
        "bucket": "pronoun.combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
        "label": "Spot the wrongly-joined pre-verb cluster",
        "any_phrases": [
          "Cela voglio dare"
        ],
        "must_not_include": [
          "Vogliamo darcelo",
          "Glielo abbiamo",
          "Te ne porto"
        ]
      }
    ],
    "vocab_help": [],
    "explanation": "The intended meaning is 'I want to give it to her'; the correct written form is 'Gliela voglio dare' (never joined as 'Cela'). Pre-verb the cluster is separated: ce la voglio dare. The 'Cela' form is the joined-when-separate error. The other three are correct: darcelo (joined post-verb), glielo (one word in either position by glielo-family rule), te ne (separated pre-verb).",
    "examiner_note": "Tests the rule by error-spotting across four cluster patterns. The glielo-family choice is a foil to test that learners don't over-apply the 'always separate pre-verb' rule to gli- forms.",
    "version": 1
  },
  {
    "external_id": "op_comb_joined_05",
    "language_code": "it",
    "topic": "pronoun",
    "subtopic": "combined.joined_when_should_be_separate",
    "difficulty": 3,
    "cefr_level_target": "B2",
